Metcash launches ground stewardship campaign to combat Aldi- intrusion
Metcash is trying to protect IGA stores from an Aldi surge in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground-breaking campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in the run-up to a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centres and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media, as well as through events such as Adelaide show.
IGA retailers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands such as ice maker Simmo from Dunsborough distributing samples at IGA stores and shoppers selling illicit tickets for the South Australian football league to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defence strategy on September 29 when the wholesaler for food, alcohol and equipment conducts its annual investor strategy day.
Much is at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 per cent of Metcash's IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the eastern states.
Shoppers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 per cent in South Australia and 24 per cent in Western Australia compared with around 14 per cent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will snap away about five per cent of the grocery market in these two states 12 months after it opens its first markets, taking away sales to all existing players but mainly self-employed retailers.
According to a report published this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales a year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
That forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year and achieve sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and food business and in volumes on Metcash's high fixed-cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and tax, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA shoppers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley accepts that Metcash's sales in the food and grocery business will fall by 3.8 per cent in 2016, by 4.1 per cent in 2017 and 2.1 per cent in 2018, and will reduce its market share from 14 per cent in 2015 to 10.3 per cent by 2020.
Last week, senior fund manager Hamish Douglass, founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash was likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr Douglass's comments.
But it is understood that a Metcash board member made contact with Mr Douglass last week.
IGAS's market share has fallen from 18 per cent to 14 per cent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash's food and grocery retailer, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43 per cent since 2012, reflecting operating debt reduction while putting pressure on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is hurting and investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths at hundreds of products each week, and to help IGA retailers improve their stores through faster growing fresh food and deliver a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash's chief executive Ian Morrice says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will go to Elan and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is backed by the president of the Australian Tennis Association Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behaviour.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to the president of the Australian Tennis Association, Steve Healy deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behaviour.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks," got into the spotlight by Kyrgios' infamous clash with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison declaring: "Wawrinka should have beat Kyrgios and I should have beat the kid."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a tie thwarted a potential US Open win by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the single behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm quite eager about is the fact that, in my view, Thanasi was dragged a little bit into the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a racquet when he lost because of a tie in the US Open, but he's not the first player to break a racquet out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he has behaved extremely well in the US Open, even in the pretty provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of credit.
He's got a great team around him, he's got a great family around and I think he's been treated a little too strictly.
He's a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard and he fits into the team and so on, he's never had a problem with the other players, he's respected in the changing area, he trains hard, he's good in form, he's a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also backed the decision not to consider Kyrgios at the important preliminary decision, which begins on Friday, describing the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the man from Canberra to return as a long-term permanent part of the team. "
"First of all, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversies round [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I believe that Nick very quickly managed to rise to what people like Federer and Murray have pointed out, he's rising in the eyes of the public, and he's made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we're trying to support him, we're trying to make him understand the consequences of his actions; some time outside the spotlight where he can only think about it, I think it's appropriate and the team is best for him.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes border, keeps refugees back
Hungary declared a state of emergency and closed the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, keeping everyone who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the flow of migrants.
Chaos followed on the border when hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man's land and Serbian officials responded with outrage.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations rose.
When a police helicopter swooped above them, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" And shouted insults at Hungarian riot police.
Some withdrew food and water from protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants would be sent back from Hungary while more and more arrive from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
There must be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days, "said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree a common immigration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels.
However, ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in outlawed Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that EU states would take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special European Union summit on Tuesday to discuss the continent's immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not pin its hopes on early action from Brussels or its neighbors.
The state of emergency struck on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis so they could shut down roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto, meanwhile, said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the flow of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were used in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck and entry point into the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most of the arrivals are economic migrants who are looking for a better life, rather than war refugees who are entitled to protection - a view that is strongly at odds with other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government built along the southern border with Serbia a crime, which laws also impose higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government is declaring the state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to give procedural approval to the deployment of the military, which is expected for next week, but reporters from Associated Press have already seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs on the border day after day.
Gyorgy Bakondi, country security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already entered the country deeper.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing offences under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of quickly repairing the fence.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train wagon with barbed wire to close the borders arrived.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process people's data and pressed a crowd to squeeze in there.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway link from Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
