That will happen when the Fed raises rates
A rate hike is coming, and the house rate will fall, bond yields will rise, and the economy will slide into recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long it will take and how long it will last.
In particular, history provides little guidance for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, though not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
So US central bank officials have emphasized so fiercely that investors should focus not on when it begins to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that all the excitement may have been exaggerated because of a rate hike.
"The Fed's first increase since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of 'cheap money'," Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a communication to clients.
By contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal levels, but still to low levels, to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, that does not mean there will be no impact.
Here's a historical trend-based look at how some areas of the economy might react:
As the market saw last month, anticipating rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase arrives, the influence is not so dramatic.
"There appears to be a tendency for asset yields to be depreciated 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after Fed rate hikes.
More specifically, over the past 35 years, the market has mostly been on the upward trajectory - about 14 per cent - on its way to the rate hike, fairly flat in the 250 days after that (average gain of 2.6 per cent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the past six past cycles of 14.4 per cent, according to a recent analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on equities tends to occur later in the increases cycle and the yield is starting to diminish.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate hikes often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely noteworthy that gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point in a Fed rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 rate hikes since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes at such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky, raising the question of "whether it's different this time," Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants got caught all year on a Fed rate hike, and all eyes were on this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading gives only a 25 percent probability.
"In our study, all the increase cycles have taken place from 1950 to the present day in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP, and pre-recession levels have been shaken up very quickly after the start of the recovery," the report said.
By contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record has been 35 months, and this is 74 months to date.
Fixed income was also volatile, as the market anticipates an interest rate hike, and the pattern is pretty much the same as in the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on equities when they change their strategic course.
On bonds, yields seem to change direction as soon as the first increase / reduction occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab's strategists believe the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to move closer together and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often yield better in such a climate, although "we are still cautious to expect higher yields," Kathy Jones, fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones thinks markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy," they wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flat, borrowing margins have expanded and volatility has risen - all characteristics of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
By and large, companies that handle the greater part of their business in the US will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinationals with high debts will be worse off, as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive on the global market, as well as financing their debts.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to react exceedingly positively three months after an initial rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Firms with a strong balance sheet have surpassed firms with weak balance sheets by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate hikes in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital yields and low volatility in their shares also surpassed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) each.
Debt is becoming a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside purely equity games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see gains through higher returns, though experts differ on how quickly that will take place.
