'Sonogenetics' can control brain cells through sound waves
The video shows how the Nematodes change direction at the moment they are irradiated with sound pulses.
Scientists have bred worms with genetically modified nervous systems that can be controlled by outbreaks of sound waves.
The tiny Nematodes change direction at the moment they are irradiated with sound pulses that have too high frequencies for human hearing to be heard.
The impulses work by turning on motoneuron cells, which are genetically modified to carry membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
More on the subject: Researchers read and write brain activity with light
The researchers said the worms showed the power of a new procedure, called sonogenetics, in which ultrasound can be used to activate a range of brain, heart and muscle cells outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the procedure could one day replace deep-brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that gives electrical impulses into people's brains to treat the symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
Thread worms don't usually respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they did when they were surrounded by a fluid with microscopic air bubbles.
The bubbles, he found, reinforce the ultrasound waves, which then penetrate into the worms.
The reinforced ultrasound waves affect structures called TRP-4 ion channels and are found in the membranes of some of the worm cells.
The sound waves cause the opening of these ion channels and activate the cells to which they are assigned, according to a report Nature Communications.
To create ultrasound-controlled neematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motoneurons carry TRP-4 ion channels.
When it applies ultrasound to the altered creatures, the sound waves are amplified by the microflies and transferred to the worms, where they turn on the modified motoneurons.
The procedure has some similarities to optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off with impulses of light.
But Chalasani said sonogenetics could have some advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent down to the desired location in the brain at an optical fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic waves can pass through tissues unhindered and can thus be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that with gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it is possible to temporarily make the cited human neurons vulnerable to the ultrasound signal in a clinical setting for certain neurological treatments," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
