Threatening over them at one end of the decorated, two-storey sitting hall is a wall image of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation's economic interests ahead of all other things.
The central bank has a double order from Congress: Maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: Financial stability.
And that third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict it, it will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to start being disenchanted from the unprecedented stimulus by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
While most of the economy's data shows it is growing solidly, recent turmoil in global financial markets could make Fed officials already cautious about amplifying that volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds - if only by a quarter percentage point.
"Obviously the labor market and inflation will primarily be the most important thing they observe," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
