The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly overweight people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
It's too early to say whether slightly overweight people with diabetes are living longer after weight loss surgery than those receiving non-surgical treatments.
"The mortality data takes a long time to show anything," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial to the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss operations, or obesity surgery, use different methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's own ability to absorb food.
Over the years, obesity operations to treat type 2 diabetes have proved efficient, but most studies have been conducted in people who are ill obese with a Body Mass Index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a degree of weight in terms of size, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates that someone is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov / 1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, the researchers from Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data they have collected in a study since 2007, comparing two types of obesity surgery - stomach bypass and stomach hose formation - to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were slightly overweight.
The average BMI among those undergoing this surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in this study.
Meanwhile, the BMI remained roughly the same among those who received non-surgical diabetes treatments at 29.
Among those undergoing surgery, 36% completely dissolved diabetes and 28% partially.
In the medically-treated group, compared to that, diabetes completely wiped out only one per cent and partly at only about two per cent.
