Robot cars: Government wants lead for Germany
Germany is supposed to be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car, according to the Federal Government.
The federal cabinet on Wednesday approved a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which envisages, among other things, investment in the development of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the Automesse IAA of a "new mobility age."
Automated and connected driving will increase road safety and ensure less congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who are also meeting with industry representatives at the IAA.
Among other things, the transport ministry's strategy paper emphasizes the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid shift to digital radio.
A test track on the motorway 9 in Bavaria is currently being developed to test new technology.
So that the driver "does not face additional liability risks," the Federal Government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to the new developments."
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum permitted speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to see an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
In automated driving, the car increasingly takes the lead, the driver becomes more and more a passenger.
The technology is based primarily on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Still, driverless vehicles on public roads are "not expected until well after 2020."
The authors of the study estimate the added value in the area of driver assistance systems and the highly automated driving functions at Germany's site for 2025 at around EUR 8.4 billion.
"Digital connectivity of the car can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road transport," said SPD transport politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the safety of the personal data of drivers must be clearly clarified.
Yet Germans still view self-driving cars skeptically - much more than French or American.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of Dekra, presented on Wednesday at the AA, concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe autonomous-driving cars will prevail in the coming decade, 32 percent expect only in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe in it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous-driving cars by 2025, up 33 percent in the U.S.
Anyway, motorists in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven per cent would agree to hand over control throughout the ride on all roads.
On the motorway, that in fluid traffic could still imagine 15 per cent, in congestion 45 per cent.
Well every fourth would not leave the car in control under any circumstances.
