XI urges to open economy wider for the world
The economy needs to open up more broadly to encourage growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday of a group tasked with steering the reform.
"China should work to attract foreign investment and expertise and improve business start-up strategies," he said in an address at the 16th session of the Central Leadership Group for deepening comprehensive reform.
Encouraging new start-ups and advancing reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list for regulating market access, relaxing border control policies, promoting state-owned enterprises (SOE) to take private capital, and overhauling the resident reporting system.
According to the statement, a negative list is being drawn up that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually being tested and improved by testing programs.
The initiative is significant as it assigns a greater role to the market in allocating resources, ensuring a rule-of-law business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers transferred to businesses and ensure that companies decide how to conduct their business.
The statement also said China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of a bid to open up government-controlled sectors, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of leveraged companies and provide better services for them," the statement said.
In addition, it makes it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the Green Card by optimizing requirements and facilitating the application process.
The right of lawyers to guarantee their work, and to employ professional judges and prosecutors, was also discussed at a meeting.
The meeting also included Premier Li Keqiang and key leaders such as Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, as reported in a statement released after the meeting.
EU wants mercury limit to double in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thereby giving consumers a significantly higher dose of nerve gifts.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding working paper from the EU, sharply criticised the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on with full force to pregnant women and toddlers," said Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of nerve poison for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be increased from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons."
Large-scale predators, however, are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that around 50% of catches cannot be sold on the basis of the limits still in force.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5% would be unsold.
In exchange for this easing, the EU, according to Foodwatch, wants to tighten the limit on other fish from the current 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
However, Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller cemeteries, such as carp, are usually so low that they already meet the planned maximum levels today.
The lowering of small-scale fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction that helps the economy alone," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which is greatly enriched through the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system especially in the case of unborn ones."
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment declares on its homepage that a "health hazard of the general population" cannot be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through coal incineration.
The German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tonnes of mercury per year, two thirds of the total emitted in Germany, according to written information from the Federal Ministry of the Environment.
The concentration of mercury in fish, such as in Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and universally exceeded," the "Mirror" quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most common reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest the EU's plans at: Www.mercury-aktion.foodwatch.de
